How a Request Reaches an EC2 Instance in a Private Subnet
ğŸ“Œ Scenario Overview
You have a web application that can be accessed using www.example.com, and it is deployed inside an EC2 instance in a private subnet. When a user enters www.example.com in their browser, the request goes through several AWS components before reaching the private EC2 instance.

âœ… The EC2 instance is in a private subnet, meaning it does not have direct internet access.
âœ… A Load Balancer (ALB/NLB) in the public subnet receives incoming traffic.
âœ… AWS Route 53 (DNS) resolves the domain name (www.example.com) to the Load Balancerâ€™s public IP.
âœ… The Load Balancer forwards the request to the EC2 instance inside the private subnet using a Target Group.
âœ… If Auto Scaling is enabled, the request may be distributed among multiple EC2 instances for high availability.

ğŸ”¹ High-Level Request Flow
pgsql
Copy code
User â†’ Route 53 (DNS) â†’ Internet Gateway â†’ Load Balancer (Public Subnet) â†’ Target Group â†’ EC2 (Private Subnet)
1ï¸âƒ£ Components Involved in the Architecture
ğŸ“Œ 1. VPC (Virtual Private Cloud)
Definition: A logically isolated network within AWS where your resources (EC2, RDS, ALB) are deployed.

Why Needed? Ensures network segmentation, security, and routing control.

Subnets: Divided into Public and Private subnets for better security and isolation.

ğŸ“Œ 2. Internet Gateway (IGW)
Definition: An AWS-managed gateway that allows traffic between the internet and public subnets.

Why Needed? The Load Balancer needs to communicate with external users via the internet.

Traffic Flow:

The Internet Gateway (IGW) connects only to Public Subnets.

Private Subnets cannot communicate with the IGW directly.

ğŸ“Œ 3. Public Subnet (Contains Load Balancer)
Definition: A subnet that has a route to the Internet Gateway (IGW).

Contains:
âœ… Application Load Balancer (ALB) or Network Load Balancer (NLB)
âœ… NAT Gateway (Optional, for Private Subnet Outbound Traffic)

ğŸ“Œ 4. Private Subnet (Contains EC2 Application Server)
Definition: A subnet without direct access to the internet.

Contains:
âœ… EC2 instance (Application Server)
âœ… RDS (Database Server, Optional)

ğŸ’¡ Important:

Private subnets cannot send outbound traffic directly to the internet.

If outbound access is needed, a NAT Gateway is required.

ğŸ“Œ 5. Route Table
Definition: A table that controls how traffic is routed inside the VPC.

Types of Route Tables:

Public Subnet Route Table

Routes public traffic to the Internet Gateway (IGW).

Example:

yaml
Copy code
Destination: 0.0.0.0/0 â†’ Target: Internet Gateway (IGW)
Private Subnet Route Table

Routes traffic to a NAT Gateway for internet access (if needed).

Example:

yaml
Copy code
Destination: 0.0.0.0/0 â†’ Target: NAT Gateway
ğŸ“Œ 6. Load Balancer (ALB/NLB)
Definition: A public-facing AWS Load Balancer that receives requests and forwards them to the EC2 instance.

Why Needed?
âœ… Distributes traffic across multiple instances (Auto Scaling).
âœ… Ensures high availability and fault tolerance.
âœ… Secures traffic with SSL/TLS termination.

Works with Target Groups to route traffic efficiently.

ğŸ“Œ 7. Target Group
Definition: A logical group that contains EC2 instances behind a Load Balancer.

Why Needed?
âœ… Ensures traffic is forwarded only to healthy EC2 instances.
âœ… Supports Auto Scaling to handle high traffic.

ğŸ“Œ 8. Auto Scaling Group
Definition: A mechanism to automatically add or remove EC2 instances based on demand.

Why Needed?
âœ… Scalability: Handles sudden traffic spikes.
âœ… High Availability: Replaces unhealthy instances automatically.

Works with Load Balancer & Target Groups to distribute requests efficiently.

2ï¸âƒ£ End-to-End Request Flow (Detailed Step-by-Step)
ğŸ”¹ Step 1: User Requests the Website
A user enters www.example.com in a browser.

ğŸ”¹ Step 2: Route 53 Resolves the Domain
AWS Route 53 (DNS) resolves www.example.com to the Load Balancerâ€™s public IP.

ğŸ”¹ Step 3: Request Goes Through the Internet Gateway
The request reaches the Internet Gateway (IGW).

IGW allows only public subnet communication.

ğŸ”¹ Step 4: Load Balancer Receives the Request
The ALB/NLB (in Public Subnet) receives the request.

ğŸ”¹ Step 5: Load Balancer Routes Traffic to Target Group
The Load Balancer checks the Target Group for healthy instances.

It forwards the request to an EC2 instance in a Private Subnet.

ğŸ”¹ Step 6: EC2 in Private Subnet Processes the Request
The EC2 instance processes the request.

It may query an RDS database if needed.

The response is sent back to the Load Balancer.

ğŸ”¹ Step 7: Load Balancer Sends the Response to the User
The Load Balancer forwards the processed response back to the user.

âœ… The user now sees the webpage from the EC2 instance inside the private subnet!

